# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-transit-gateway
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP used for routing within an autonomous system is called **Interior Border Gateway Protocol** (**iBGP**).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In contrast, the Internet application of the protocol is called **Exterior Border Gateway Protocol** (**EBGP**).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In January 1989, at the 12th IETF meeting in Austin, Texas, Yakov Rekhter, Len Bosack, and Kirk Lougheed sat down at a table to design what ultimately became the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The initial BGP design was recorded on two napkins, hence often referenced to as the “Two-Napkin Protocol”.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The design on the napkins was expanded to three hand-written sheets of paper from which the first interoperable BGP implementation was quickly developed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A photocopy of these three sheets of paper now hangs on the wall of a routing protocol development area at Cisco Systems in Milpitas, California.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the same year, RFC 1105 was published, and the BGP protocol (in various forms) has been in use on the Internet since 1994.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Half a year after the initial publication, the protocol definition was changed in 1990 with the publication of RFC 1136.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In October 1991, BGP version 3 was defined in RFC 1267, obsoleting the two earlier versions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 1994, the current version (BGP4), was published as RFC 1654.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Its definition was replaced in March 1995 by RFC 1771.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In January 2006, RFC 4271 was published, which currently is the latest definition of BGP4 (although updated by many other RFCs).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RFC 4271 corrected errors, clarified ambiguities and updated the specification with common industry practices.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The major enhancement of BGP4 was the support for Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and use of route aggregation to decrease the size of routing tables.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In its native form, the BGP4 protocol can only work with IPv4 addresses.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Since the publication of RFC 2283 in 1998, routing information about a wide range of "address families" (IPv4, IPv6, IPX, etc.) can be carried.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The 'Multiprotocol Extensions' have been updated in 2000 with RFC 2858 and finally in 2007 with RFC 4760.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With these extensions, the protocol is also referred to as Multiprotocol BGP (MP-BGP).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP neighbors, called peers, are established by manual configuration among routers to create a TCP session on port 179.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A BGP speaker sends 19-byte keep-alive messages every 30 seconds (protocol default value, tunable) to maintain the connection.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Among routing protocols, BGP is unique in using TCP as its transport protocol.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] When BGP runs between two peers in the same autonomous system (AS), it is referred to as *Internal BGP* (*iBGP* or *Interior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] When it runs between different autonomous systems, it is called *External BGP* (*eBGP* or *Exterior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Routers on the boundary of one AS exchanging information with another AS are called *border* or *edge routers* or simply *eBGP peers* and are typically connected directly, while *iBGP peers* can be interconnected through other intermediate routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Other deployment topologies are also possible, such as running eBGP peering inside a VPN tunnel, allowing two remote sites to exchange routing information in a secure and isolated manner.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These route-propagation rules effectively require that all iBGP peers inside an AS are interconnected in a full mesh with iBGP sessions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] How routes are propagated can be controlled in detail via the *route-maps* mechanism.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This mechanism consists of a set of rules.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Each rule describes, for routes matching some given criteria, what action should be taken.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The action could be to drop the route, or it could be to modify some attributes of the route before inserting it in the routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] During the peering handshake, when OPEN messages are exchanged, BGP speakers can negotiate optional capabilities of the session, including multiprotocol extensions and various recovery modes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the multiprotocol extensions to BGP are negotiated at the time of creation, the BGP speaker can prefix the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) it advertises with an address family prefix.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These families include the IPv4 (default), IPv6, IPv4/IPv6 Virtual Private Networks and multicast BGP.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Increasingly, BGP is used as a generalized signaling protocol to carry information about routes that may not be part of the global Internet, such as VPNs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In order to make decisions in its operations with peers, a BGP peer uses a simple finite-state machine (FSM) that consists of six states: Idle; Connect; Active; OpenSent; OpenConfirm; and Established.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For each peer-to-peer session, a BGP implementation maintains a state variable that tracks which of these six states the session is in.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP defines the messages that each peer should exchange in order to change the session from one state to another.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Idle state, BGP initializes all resources, refuses all inbound BGP connection attempts and initiates a TCP connection to the peer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Connect state, the router waits for the TCP connection to complete and transitions to the OpenSent state if successful.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If unsuccessful, it starts the ConnectRetry timer and transitions to the Active state upon expiration.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Active state, the router resets the ConnectRetry timer to zero and returns to the Connect state.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the OpenSent state, the router sends an Open message and waits for one in return in order to transition to the OpenConfirm state.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Keepalive messages are exchanged and, upon successful receipt, the router is placed into the Established state.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Established state, the router can send and receive: Keepalive; Update; and Notification messages to and from its peer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the simplest arrangement, all routers within a single AS and participating in BGP routing must be configured in a full mesh: each router must be configured as a peer to every other router.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This causes scaling problems, since the number of required connections grows quadratically with the number of routers involved.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To alleviate the problem, BGP implements two options: route reflectors (RFC 4456) and BGP confederations (RFC 5065).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The following discussion of basic update processing assumes a full iBGP mesh.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A given BGP router may accept network-layer reachability information (NLRI) updates from multiple neighbors and advertise NLRI to the same, or a different set, of neighbors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The physical storage and structure of these conceptual tables are decided by the implementer of the BGP code.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Their structure is not visible to other BGP routers, although they usually can be interrogated with management commands on the local router.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is quite common, for example, to store the `Adj-RIB-In`, `Adj-RIB-Out` and the `Loc-RIB` together in the same data structure, with additional information attached to the RIB entries.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP submits the routes that it considers best to the main routing table process.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Depending on the implementation of that process, the BGP route is not necessarily selected.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example, a directly connected prefix, learned from the router's own hardware, is usually most preferred.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As long as that directly connected route's interface is active, the BGP route to the destination will not be put into the routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Once the interface goes down and there are no more preferred routes, the Loc-RIB route would be installed in the main routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP carries the information with which rules inside BGP-speaking routers can make policy decisions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP standard specifies a number of decision factors, more than the ones that are used by any other common routing process, for selecting NLRI to go into the Loc-RIB.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The first decision point for evaluating NLRI is that its next-hop attribute must be reachable (or resolvable).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another way of saying the next-hop must be reachable is that there must be an active route, already in the main routing table of the router, to the prefix in which the next-hop address is reachable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Next, for each neighbor, the BGP process applies various standard and implementation-dependent criteria to decide which routes conceptually should go into the Adj-RIB-In.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The neighbor could send several possible routes to a destination, but the first level of preference is at the neighbor level.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Only one route to each destination will be installed in the conceptual Adj-RIB-In.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This process will also delete, from the Adj-RIB-In, any routes that are withdrawn by the neighbor.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Whenever a conceptual Adj-RIB-In changes, the main BGP process decides if any of the neighbor's new routes are preferred to routes already in the Loc-RIB.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If a given route is withdrawn by a neighbor, and there is no other route to that destination, the route is removed from the Loc-RIB and no longer sent by BGP to the main routing table manager.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the router does not have a route to that destination from any non-BGP source, the withdrawn route will be removed from the main routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As long as there is a tie, the route selection process moves to the next step.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The local preference, weight, and other criteria can be manipulated by local configuration and software capabilities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Such manipulation, although commonly used, is outside the scope of the standard.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example, the *community* attribute (see below) is not directly used by the BGP selection process.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP neighbor process can have a rule to set local preference or another factor based on a manually programmed rule to set the attribute if the community value matches some pattern-matching criterion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the route was learned from an external peer the per-neighbor BGP process computes a local preference value from local policy rules and then compares the local preference of all routes from the neighbor.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP communities are attribute tags that can be applied to incoming or outgoing prefixes to achieve some common goal.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While it is common to say that BGP allows an administrator to set policies on how prefixes are handled by ISPs, this is generally not possible, strictly speaking.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For instance, BGP natively has no concept to allow one AS to tell another AS to restrict advertisement of a prefix to only North American peering customers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Instead, an ISP generally publishes a list of well-known or proprietary communities with a description for each one, which essentially becomes an agreement of how prefixes are to be treated.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The customer simply adjusts their configuration to include the correct community or communities for each route, and the ISP is responsible for controlling who the prefix is advertised to.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The end user has no technical ability to enforce correct actions being taken by the ISP, though problems in this area are generally rare and accidental.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is a common tactic for end customers to use BGP communities (usually ASN:70,80,90,100) to control the local preference the ISP assigns to advertised routes instead of using MED (the effect is similar).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The community attribute is transitive, but communities applied by the customer very rarely propagate outside the next-hop AS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Not all ISPs give out their communities to the public.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP Extended Community Attribute was added in 2006, in order to extend the range of such attributes and to provide a community attribute structuring by means of a type field.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The extended format consists of one or two octets for the type field, followed by seven or six octets for the respective community attribute content.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The IANA administers the registry for BGP Extended Communities Types.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The Extended Communities Attribute itself is a transitive optional BGP attribute.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A bit in the *Type* field within the attribute decides whether the encoded extended community is of a transitive or non-transitive nature.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The IANA registry therefore provides different number ranges for the attribute types.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Due to the extended attribute range, its usage can be manifold.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RFC 4360 exemplarily defines the "Two-Octet AS Specific Extended Community", the "IPv4 Address Specific Extended Community", the "Opaque Extended Community", the "Route Target Community", and the "Route Origin Community".
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A number of BGP QoS drafts also use this Extended Community Attribute structure for inter-domain QoS signalling.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With the introduction of 32-bit AS numbers, some issues were immediately obvious with the community attribute that only defines a 16-bit ASN field, which prevents the matching between this field and the real ASN value.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Since 2014, extended communities are compatible with 32-bit ASNs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To accommodate 32-bit AS numbers in BGP Communities, a Large Community attribute of 12 bytes was defined, divided in three field of 4 bytes each (AS:function:parameter).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] MEDs, defined in the main BGP standard, were originally intended to show to another neighbor AS the advertising AS's preference as to which of several links are preferred for inbound traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another application of MEDs is to advertise the value, typically based on delay, of multiple ASs that have a presence at an IXP, that they impose to send traffic to some destination.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Some routers (like Juniper) will use the Metric from OSPF to set MED.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] All BGP messages share the following header layout.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Included for compatibility, MUST be set to all ones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Total length of the message in octets, including the header.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With an *Open* packet, a BGP session may be initiated.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Timeout timer, used to calculate KeepAlive messages.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Total length of the Parameters field in octets.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] field is zero, there are no parameters in the message.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field is used to convey the capabilities the sender of this packet has to the peer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] After the initial exchange, only differences (add/change/remove) are sent.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Length of the following withdrawn routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Length of the following path attributes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Reachability information, specified as a series of <length, prefix> tuples.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If there is an error, it is because one of the fields in the OPEN or UPDATE message does not match between the peers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example: BGP version mismatch, or the peering router expects a different 'My AS'.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The router then sends a Notification message to the peer indicating why the error occurred.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An error in the communication usually leads to the teardown of the BGP session.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To avoid a cascade of sessions being terminated due to a single error, which can happen in complex scenarios with routers with limited capabilities, extra effort is taken to isolate the problem and keep most sessions going.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A value indicating the type or origin of the error.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A value specifying which error occurred.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Optional data to help diagnose the problem.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] KeepAlive messages are sent periodically, by both peers of a session, to verify that the remote peer is still alive.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] They should be sent at intervals of one third the `holdtime`.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A keep-alive packet has no data content.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An addition to the initial BGP message types is route-refresh, which allows for soft updating of `Adj-RIB-in`, without resetting the connection.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Before making use of this feature, the capability 'Route Refresh Capability (2)' should be specified in the 'Open' message.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Fine-grained routing updates may be acquired when the capability 'Enhanced Route Refresh Capability (70)' is also given.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field indicates what kind of route-refresh message this is.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field provides additional information about the type of the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) carried in the attribute.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An autonomous system with internal BGP (iBGP) must have all of its iBGP peers connect to each other in a full mesh (where everyone speaks to everyone directly).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This full-mesh configuration requires that each router maintain a session with every other router.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In large networks, this number of sessions may degrade the performance of routers, due to either a lack of memory or high CPU process requirements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This approach, similar to OSPF's DR/BDR feature, provides large networks with added iBGP scalability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In a fully meshed iBGP network of 10 routers, 90 individual CLI statements (spread throughout all routers in the topology) are needed just to define the remote-AS of each peer: this quickly becomes a headache to manage.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An RR topology can cut these 90 statements down to 18, offering a viable solution for the larger networks administered by ISPs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An RR is a single point of failure, therefore at least a second RR may be configured in order to provide redundancy.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As it is an additional peer for the other 10 routers, it approximately doubles the number of CLI statements, requiring an additional 11 × 2 − 2 = 20 statements in this case.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In a BGP multipath environment, the additional RR can also benefit the network by adding local routing throughput if the RRs are acting as traditional routers instead of just a dedicated RR server role.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RRs and confederations both reduce the number of iBGP peers to each router and thus reduce processing overhead.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RRs are a pure performance-enhancing technique, while confederations can also be used to implement more fine-grained policy.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The *cluster ID* is then attached to every route advertised by the RR to its client or non-client peers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A cluster ID is a cumulative, non-transitive BGP attribute, and every RR must prepend the local cluster ID to the cluster list to avoid routing loops.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations are sets of autonomous systems.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In common practice, only one of the confederation AS numbers is seen by the Internet as a whole.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations are used in very large networks where a large AS can be configured to encompass smaller, more manageable internal ASs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The confederated AS is composed of multiple ASs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Each confederated AS alone has iBGP fully meshed and has connections to other ASs inside the confederation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Even though these ASs have eBGP peers to ASs within the confederation, the ASs exchange routing as if they used iBGP.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In this way, the confederation preserves next hop, metric, and local preference information.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To the outside world, the confederation appears to be a single AS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With this solution, iBGP transit AS problems can be resolved as iBGP requires a full mesh between all BGP routers: a large number of TCP sessions and unnecessary duplication of routing traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations can be used in conjunction with route reflectors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Both confederations and route reflectors can be subject to persistent oscillation unless specific design rules, affecting both BGP and the interior routing protocol, are followed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Additionally, route reflectors and BGP confederations were not designed to ease BGP router configuration.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Nevertheless, these are common tools for experienced BGP network architects.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These tools may be combined, for example, as a hierarchy of route reflectors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The routing tables managed by a BGP implementation are adjusted continually to reflect actual changes in the network, such as links or routers going down and coming back up.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the network as a whole, it is normal for these changes to happen almost continuously, but for any particular router or link, changes are expected to be relatively infrequent.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If a router is misconfigured or mismanaged, then it may get into a rapid cycle between down and up states.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This pattern of repeated withdrawal and re-announcement, known as route flapping can cause excessive activity in all the other routers that know about the cycling entity, as the same route is continually injected and withdrawn from the routing tables.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP design is such that delivery of traffic may not function while routes are being updated.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On the Internet, a BGP routing change may cause outages for several minutes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A feature known as *route flap damping* is built into many BGP implementations, in an attempt to mitigate the effects of route flapping.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Without damping, the excessive activity can cause a heavy processing load on routers, which may in turn delay updates on other routes, and so affect overall routing stability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With damping, a route's flapping is exponentially decayed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At the first instance, when a route becomes unavailable and quickly reappears, damping does not take effect, so as to maintain the normal fail-over times of BGP.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At the second occurrence, BGP shuns that prefix for a certain length of time; subsequent occurrences are ignored exponentially longer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] After the abnormalities have ceased and a suitable length of time has passed for the offending route, prefixes can be reinstated with a clean slate.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Damping can also mitigate denial-of-service attacks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is also suggested that route flap damping is a feature more desirable if implemented to Exterior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (eBGP sessions or simply called exterior peers) and not on Interior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (iBGP sessions or simply called internal peers).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With this approach when a route flaps inside an autonomous system, it is not propagated to the external ASs – flapping a route to an eBGP will cause a chain of flapping for the particular route throughout the backbone.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This method also successfully avoids the overhead of route flap damping for iBGP sessions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Subsequent research has shown that flap damping can actually lengthen convergence times in some cases, and can cause interruptions in connectivity even when links are not flapping.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Moreover, as backbone links and router processors have become faster, some network architects have suggested that flap damping may not be as important as it used to be, since changes to the routing table can be handled much faster by routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This has led the RIPE Routing Working Group to write, "With the current implementations of BGP flap damping, the application of flap damping in ISP networks is NOT recommended. ...
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If flap damping is implemented, the ISP operating that network will cause side-effects to their customers and the Internet users of their customers' content and services ... .
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] One of the largest problems faced by BGP, and indeed the Internet infrastructure as a whole, is the growth of the Internet routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the global routing table grows to the point where some older, less capable routers cannot cope with the memory requirements or the CPU load of maintaining the table, these routers will cease to be effective gateways between the parts of the Internet they connect.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In addition, and perhaps even more importantly, larger routing tables take longer to stabilize after a major connectivity change, leaving network service unreliable, or even unavailable, in the interim.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Until late 2001, the global routing table was growing exponentially, threatening an eventual widespread breakdown of connectivity.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In an attempt to prevent this, ISPs cooperated in keeping the global routing table as small as possible by using Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and route aggregation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While this slowed the growth of the routing table to a linear process for several years, with the expanded demand for multihoming by end-user networks, the growth was once again superlinear by the middle of 2004.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A Y2K-like overflow triggered in 2014 for those models that were not appropriately updated.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While a full IPv4 BGP table as of August 2014 (512k day) was in excess of 512,000 prefixes, many older routers had a limit of 512k (512,000–524,288) routing table entries.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On August 12, 2014, outages resulting from full tables hit eBay, LastPass and Microsoft Azure, among others.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A number of Cisco routers commonly in use had TCAM, a form of high-speed content-addressable memory, for storing BGP advertised routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On impacted routers, the TCAM was by default allocated as 512k IPv4 routes and 256k IPv6 routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While the reported number of IPv6 advertised routes was only about 20k, the number of advertised IPv4 routes reached the default limit, causing a spillover effect as routers attempted to compensate for the issue by using slow software routing (as opposed to fast hardware routing via TCAM).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The main method for dealing with this issue involves operators changing the TCAM allocation to allow more IPv4 entries by reallocating some of the TCAM reserved for IPv6 routes, which requires a reboot on most routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The 512k problem was predicted by a number of IT professionals.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The actual allocations, which pushed the number of routes above 512k, were the announcement of about 15,000 new routes in short order, starting at 07:48 UTC.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Almost all of these routes were to Verizon Autonomous Systems 701 and 705, created as a result of the deaggregation of larger blocks, introducing thousands of new */24* routes, and making the routing table reach 515,000 entries.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The new routes appear to have been reaggregated within 5 minutes, but instability across the Internet apparently continued for a number of hours.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Even if Verizon had not caused the routing table to exceed 512k entries in the short spike, it would have soon happened through natural growth.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Route summarization is often used to improve aggregation of the BGP global routing table, thereby reducing the necessary table size in routers of an AS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This all counts as AS1 announcing four routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At AS1, it will either be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back, depending on the configuration of AS1's routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If AS2 now wants to send data to prefix *172.16.192.0/18*, it will be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back at the routers of AS2 (not AS1 as before), because *172.16.192.0/18* is not in the routing table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 1995, the first BGP-4 specification coded AS numbers on 16 bits, for 64,510 possible public AS numbers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 2011, only 15,000 AS numbers were still available, and projections were envisioning a complete depletion of available AS numbers in September 2013.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 2007 already, the AS coding was extended from 16 to 32 bits, while retaining the 16-bit AS range (0 to 65535) and its reserved AS numbers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This now allows up to 4 billion available AS numbers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An additional private AS range is also defined.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To allow the traversal of router groups not able to manage those new ASNs, the new attribute **AS4_PATH** (optional transitive) and the special 16-bit ASN **AS_TRANS** (AS23456) is used.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another factor contributing to the growth of the routing table is the need for load balancing of multi-homed networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is not a trivial task to balance the inbound traffic to a multi-homed network across its multiple inbound paths, due to limitations of the BGP route selection process.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For a multi-homed network, if it announces the same network blocks across all of its BGP peers, the result may be that one or several of its inbound links become congested while the other links remain under-utilized, because external networks all picked that set of congested paths as optimal.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Like most other routing protocols, BGP does not detect congestion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Such cases will increase the number of routes as seen on the global BGP table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] One method to address the routing table issue associated with load balancing is to deploy Locator/Identifier Separation Protocol (BGP/LISP) gateways within an Internet exchange point to allow ingress traffic engineering across multiple links.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This technique does not increase the number of routes seen on the global BGP table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] By design, routers running BGP accept advertised routes from other BGP routers by default.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This allows for automatic and decentralized routing of traffic across the Internet, but it also leaves the Internet potentially vulnerable to accidental or malicious disruption, known as BGP hijacking.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Multiprotocol Extensions for BGP (MBGP), sometimes referred to as Multiprotocol BGP or Multicast BGP and defined in RFC 4760, is an extension to BGP that allows different types of addresses (known as address families) to be distributed in parallel.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Whereas standard BGP supports only IPv4 unicast addresses, Multiprotocol BGP supports IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and it supports unicast and multicast variants of each.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Multiprotocol BGP allows information about the topology of IP multicast-capable routers to be exchanged separately from the topology of normal IPv4 unicast routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Thus, it allows a multicast routing topology different from the unicast routing topology.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Although MBGP enables the exchange of inter-domain multicast routing information, other protocols, such as the Protocol Independent Multicast family, are needed to build trees and forward multicast traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Another extension to BGP is multipath routing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] This typically requires identical MED, weight, origin, and AS-path, although some implementations provide the ability to relax the AS-path checking to only expect an equal path length rather than the actual AS numbers in the path being expected to match too.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] This can then be extended further with features like Cisco's dmzlink-bw which enables a ratio of traffic sharing based on bandwidth values configured on individual links.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] By default, BGP only supports the advertisement of a single locally selected best path to its neighbors through its Update messages.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] RFC 7911 defines the **ADD-PATH** extension, which allows a BGP speaker to advertise multiple paths for the same destination to peers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] One application for this is when using route reflectors (RRs), because then the RR can advertise all known route paths to its clients, instead of sending only a single route it selected based on its local decision process, which is likely not the best path for all of its clients.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] BGP4 is standard for Internet routing and required of most Internet service providers (ISPs) to establish routing between one another.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Very large private IP networks use BGP internally.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] An example use case is the joining of a number of large Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) networks when OSPF by itself does not scale to the size required.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Another reason to use BGP is multihoming a network for better redundancy, either to multiple access points to a single ISP or to multiple ISPs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Routers, especially small ones intended for small office/home office (SOHO) use, may not include BGP capability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Other commercial routers may need a specific software executable image that supports BGP, or a license that enables it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Devices marketed as layer-3 switches are less likely to support BGP than devices marketed as routers, but many high-end layer-3 switches can run BGP.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Products marketed as switches may have a size limitation on BGP tables that is far smaller than a full Internet table plus internal routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] A BGP router used only for a network with a single point of entry to the Internet may have a much smaller routing table size (and hence RAM and CPU requirements) than a multihomed network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Even simple multihoming can have a modest routing table size.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The actual amount of memory required in a BGP router depends on the amount of BGP information exchanged with other BGP speakers and the way in which the particular router stores BGP information.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The router may have to keep more than one copy of a route, so it can manage different policies for route advertising and acceptance to a specific neighboring AS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The term *view* is often used for these different policy relationships on a running router.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] If one router implementation takes more memory per route than another implementation, this may be a legitimate design choice, trading processing speed against memory.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] A full IPv4 BGP table as of September 2025 is in excess of one million prefixes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Large ISPs may add another 50% for internal and customer routes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Again, depending on implementation, separate tables may be kept for each view of a different peer AS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] In computing, **network virtualization** is the process of combining hardware and software network resources and network functionality into a single, software-based administrative entity, a **virtual network**.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Network virtualization involves platform virtualization, often combined with resource virtualization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Network virtualization is categorized as either **external virtualization**, combining many networks or parts of networks into a virtual unit, or **internal virtualization**, providing network-like functionality to software containers on a single network server.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] In software testing, software developers use network virtualization to test software which are under development in a simulation of the network environments in which the software is intended to operate.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] As a component of application performance engineering, network virtualization enables developers to emulate connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users in a test environment without having to physically test the software on all possible hardware or system software.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] The validity of the test depends on the accuracy of the network virtualization in emulating real hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] External network virtualization combines or subdivides one or more local area networks (LANs) into virtual networks to improve a large network's or data center's efficiency.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] A virtual local area network (VLAN) and network switch comprise the key components.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Using this technology, a system administrator can configure systems physically attached to the same local network into separate virtual networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Conversely, an administrator can combine systems on separate local area networks (LANs) into a single VLAN spanning segments of a large network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] External network virtualization is envisioned to be placed in the middle of the network stack and help integrating different architectures proposed for next generation networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Citrix and Vyatta have built a virtual network protocol stack combining Vyatta's routing, firewall, and VPN functions with Citrix's Netscaler load balancer, branch repeater wide area network (WAN) optimization, and secure sockets layer VPN.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] OpenSolaris network virtualization provides a so-called "network in a box" (see OpenSolaris Network Virtualization and Resource Control).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Microsoft Virtual Server uses virtual machines to make a "network in a box" for x86 systems.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] These containers can run different operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows or Linux, either associated with or independent of a specific network interface controller (NIC).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Network virtualization may be used in application development and testing to mimic real-world hardware and system software.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] In application performance engineering, network virtualization enables emulation of connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users for software testing.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Wireless network virtualization can have a very broad scope ranging from spectrum sharing, infrastructure virtualization, to air interface virtualization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] In other words, virtualization, regardless of wired or wireless networks, can be considered as a process splitting the entire network system.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] However, the distinctive properties of the wireless environment, in terms of time-various channels, attenuation, mobility, broadcast, etc., make the problem more complicated.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Therefore, it may be inaccurate to consider wireless network virtualization as a subset of network virtualization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Until 1 Gbit/s networks, network virtualization was not suffering from the overhead of the software layers or hypervisor layers providing the interconnects.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] With the rise of high bandwidth, 10 Gbit/s and beyond, the rates of packets exceed the capabilities of processing of the networking stacks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] For example, in case of Openstack, network is provided by Neutron which leverages many features from the Linux kernel for networking: iptables, iproute2, L2 bridge, L3 routing or OVS.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] Since the Linux kernel cannot sustain the 10G packet rate, then some bypass technologies for a fast path are used.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/network-virtualization] The main bypass technologies are either based on a limited set of features such as Open vSwitch (OVS) with its DPDK user space implementation or based on a full feature and offload of Linux processing such as 6WIND virtual accelerator.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] A **wide area network** (**WAN**) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily functions regardless of location.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Many WANs are, however, built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] WANs can be separated from local area networks (LANs) in that the latter refers to physically proximal networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] The textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] However, in terms of the application of communication protocols and concepts, it may be best to view WANs as computer networking technologies used to transmit data over long distances, and between different networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] WANs are used to connect LANs and other types of networks together so that users and computers in one location can communicate with users and computers in other locations.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Many WANs are built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Others, built by Internet service providers, provide connections from an organization's LAN to the Internet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] WANs are often built using leased lines.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] At each end of the leased line, a router connects the LAN on one side with a second router within the LAN on the other.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Because leased lines can be very expensive, instead of using leased lines, WANs can also be built using less costly circuit switching or packet switching methods.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Network protocols, including TCP/IP, deliver transport and addressing functions.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Protocols including Packet over SONET/SDH, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Frame Relay are often used by service providers to deliver the links that are used in WANs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] It is also possible to build a WAN with Ethernet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Academic research into wide area networks can be broken down into three areas: mathematical models, network emulation, and network simulation.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Performance improvements are sometimes delivered via wide area file services or WAN optimization.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Of the approximately four billion addresses defined in IPv4, about 18 million addresses in three ranges are reserved for use in private networks.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Packets addressed in these ranges are not routable on the public Internet; they are ignored by all public routers.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Therefore, private hosts cannot directly communicate with public networks, but require network address translation at a routing gateway for this purpose.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Additionally, encapsulated packets may be encrypted to secure their data.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Many technologies are available for wide-area network links.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Examples include circuit-switched telephone lines, radio wave transmission, and optical fiber.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] New developments have successively increased transmission rates.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] 1960, a 110 bit/s line was normal on the edge of the WAN, while core links of 56 or 64 kbit/s were considered fast.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Today, households are connected to the Internet with dial-up, asymmetric digital subscriber line (ADSL), cable, WiMAX, cellular network or fiber.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] The speeds that people can currently use range from 28.8 kbit/s through a 28K modem over a telephone connection to speeds as high as 100 Gbit/s using 100 Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] The following communication and networking technologies have been used to implement WANs.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] AT&T conducted trials in 2017 for business use of 400-gigabit Ethernet.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Researchers Robert Maher, Alex Alvarado, Domaniç Lavery, and Polina Bayvel of University College London were able to increase networking speeds to 1.125 terabits per second.
[src:aws-transit-gateway/wide-area-network] Christos Santis, graduate student Scott Steger, Amnon Yariv, Martin and Eileen Summerfield developed a new laser that potentially quadruples transfer speeds with fiber optics.
